2026-04-21 | Minimum Hamming Distance After Allowed Swaps

Question
Return minimum Hamming distance after optimal swaps.
	Key Insight
Swaps create **connected components**.  
Within each component:
		you can rearrange elements freely  
So:
→ treat each component independently  
	Approach
1.	Use DSU (Union-Find):
		connect indices using allowedSwaps  
2.	Group indices by parent  
3.	For each group:
		count frequency of source elements  
4.	Compare with target:
		for each index in group:
			if target element exists in frequency:
				decrease count  
			else:
				mismatch++  
	Time Complexity
	O(n α(n))
	Space Complexity
	O(n)
	Solution
class Solution {
public:
    vector<int> parent;
    int find(int x){
        if(parent[x] != x)
            parent[x] = find(parent[x]);
        return parent[x];
    }
    void unite(int a, int b){
        parent[find(a)] = find(b);
    }
    int minimumHammingDistance(vector<int>& source,
                               vector<int>& target,
                               vector<vector<int>>& allowedSwaps) {
        int n = source.size();
        parent.resize(n);
        for(int i=0;i<n;i++) parent[i] = i;
        for(auto &e : allowedSwaps){
            unite(e[0], e[1]);
        }
        unordered_map<int, vector<int>> groups;
        for(int i=0;i<n;i++){
            groups[find(i)].push_back(i);
        }
        int mismatch = 0;
        for(auto &g : groups){
            unordered_map<int,int> freq;
            for(int idx : g.second){
                freq[source[idx]]++;
            }
            for(int idx : g.second){
                if(freq[target[idx]] > 0){
                    freq[target[idx]]--;
                } else {
                    mismatch++;
                }
            }
        }
        return mismatch;
    }
};
	Key Insight
Inside each connected component:
		we can rearrange freely  
So problem reduces to:
		matching frequencies between source and target per component  
This avoids brute-force swapping entirely.
